Esa Decides on Large Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects they want to launch in the coming years.
Thirty proposals were selected, five are still in the race.
distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets in other stars have already been found by astronomers.
At least some of them are alive, no one knows.
The choice is hard: Should you look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or wander to Earth-like planets and perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These questions are being asked by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to significantly advance research.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were up for debate, five of which have now come to the narrower election.
Numerous committees reviewed the proposals, following in the footsteps of the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be made by the Scientific Programme Committee.
In total, Esa has selected four major questions to which the missions of the program "Cosmic Vision" initiated in 2007 are to find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes involved in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars – are still in the proverbial darkness.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To address this issue, the Cheops Space Telescope is set to launch in 2017 to study 500 already known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for “biomarkers”: gases that are considered an indicator of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question is also intended to provide information on what conditions exist for the creation of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter", ESA has already approved an M-class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is expected to launch in 2017 and closely observe the sun’s surface and activity.
Of great interest to the researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, ESA plans the first of the three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The probe "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later it reaches Jupiter and is supposed to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europa, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory, under which all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into existence and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter known to us, consisting of stars, planets and living things like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, through whose actions the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of seconds of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With Euclid, Esa has already approved an M-Mission, the launch of which is planned for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is to study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky, thus allowing conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chance of obtaining a permit as an L-mission is "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
This includes changes in the structure of spacetime that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to this day.
Elisa could make it, the scientists hope behind the project.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes that will be stationed in space.
