What happens on the go with my email?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was e-mail technically implemented in the design of the Internet service similar to the traditional mail?
When designing the early Internet services, the focus was on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols did not pay attention to creating a stable basis for a secure exchange of letters.
Therefore, a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the two computers connected directly?
In the first step, Anna’s email program or browser sends the email to the mail server of its service provider.
For example, if you have a Gmail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can run over several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are traditional emails being read on their way through the network?
Most emails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is a annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away in a spam folder.
