So, not really a story.
And one that has already come so far in the years that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the “independence means passport control” duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should we expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European pipe?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels yoke, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has come to naught.
With the Euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties are gaining ground that are hostile to the EU or want to toss the euro overboard as a Community currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – which was only founded this year – won nearly five million votes in the September Bundestag election, effectively expelling the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the compulsory jacket, which the respective national economy is forced to stick to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has tied its members to exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians like to do that.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current state and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives imposed by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s wage fixings do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany at bay and raise Paris on par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy, and Europe has pushed its own economic policy, with which the battered French economy has to fight.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election, bringing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among working-class white Frenchmen?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in this election – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to make: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold on to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the UK to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering itself with the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can hide somewhere.
I suspect that Scotland could do very well in a looser European union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour finance minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition have been responsible for.
It would be ludicrous for Scotland to now opt for independence, only to then be forced into austerity by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Growing Up Faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty more than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe that epidemic obesity is a trigger for early puberty.
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter is already growing breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming down parents – usually this is not a sign that puberty is coming quickly,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious displays of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, appear in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there was only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (the appearance of the first regular bleeding) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When breast development begins, it takes at least two to three years to menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what actually marks the beginning of puberty, but it is considered “frozen” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endicronologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatment methods to delay an early menstruation and ward off another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for a drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the speed of development, the rate of growth and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reticent about drugs, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can alleviate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings, unlike their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They are concerned about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” said Kaplowitz.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter got her 10 days.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home scared and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causal.
Boys, like girls, enter puberty early.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, which establishes a link between body fat and puberty.
Other studies support this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, an early puberty seems to be affected by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full-blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected,” advised Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need the assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
