Pfandh<0xC3><0xA4>user booms in Singapore as crisis arrives in the middle class
In a pawnshop in Singapore’s Bendemeer shopping centre, Janani Amirthalinga trades in a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters’ school fees.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so there’s all my money in it,” Amirthalinga says.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) each month as an administrative assistant and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is rising – is so high that ValueMax, where it traded, became the third pawnshop listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Pledging jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent demanded by the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no credit check or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawnshops after families feel the pressure of rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in developed economies, families with lower and middle incomes are looking for pawnshops to make up for the difference in a stifling economy.
This week, the rating agency called Standard & Poor’s rising household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore, according to the agency, have the highest household debt in Asia relative to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing weakness in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
“Ultimately, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” said Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have further strengthened the trend to pledge personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city’s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20 percent increase in customer base in recent months in its stores.
The growth in the pawn shop is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeeer branch and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing that with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders were caught in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offered lower interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly raise debt.
“Customers lend items they already own, and the liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase the budget cover,” she explains.
The pawnshop business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use mortgages are in financial difficulties.
Wealthy people from Singapore also come to ValueMax’s stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers from all walks of life come to us.
“These include wealthy people who lend something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
