FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but not make phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices from departure to landing to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not make phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented, depending on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and the rules for stowing equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the status of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers have to switch off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to restart until the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must turn them off again and must not restart before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft refitted for use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Attendant Professional Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” said Glading.
To be honest, we are sorry to have to feel like a warden on this subject.
Nevertheless, internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data under three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So there’s still no “Words With Friends,” the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he publicly had to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to switch off the device while the plane was parked at the airport.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA, has the power to regulate telephone calls.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national traffic safety expert, told CBS News that mobile phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also interfere with air masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee, set up by the FAA to investigate the issue, recommended last month that the government allow for wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri argue that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, this is the case, which up to a third of passengers forget or ignore to turn off the device.
The FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travelers after reports of malfunctions of navigation and communication devices by VHF radios carried by passengers became known, which at the time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also so designed and approved by the FAA that they don’t mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for several years now when the flight altitude has been reached.
The airplanes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when flipping.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the proponents of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but none could detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption by the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only occasional reports of pilots talking about a disruption of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange for passengers to switch off the equipment when landing instruments under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable fit for travelers who would be extensively equipped with technology today.
“We are pleased that the FAA is recognizing that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
