Scientists were able to shed more light on the context in which a dog’s tail wagging is related to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail walked more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right halves of the brain respond differently to stimuli that elicit positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tailings of their peers, the researchers monitored the animals while watching these films of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four legs and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the cock once moves in one direction, once in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a natural version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (from the walking dog’s perspective), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the dog’s perspective, which sways), then their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience what movements they should be worried about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wagging of the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right is important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it comes to a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog if its ‘tail’ sways to the left rather than to the right rather than to become restless – the exact opposite than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that the dogs in the different studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won’t be long before we understand why the cock sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
