When I finish my patient records in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and a speech could take my breath away.
The election became a landslide victory and newscasters stopped to face the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates were crying for joy and my parents were collecting all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, as if you are being ripped out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and versatile things that Obama has accomplished, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act on health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced confiscation of homosexuality in the military, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that the party’s political blockade tactics have overturned too many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name but a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end with my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political desperation.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why foreign heads of state are allowed to be interrogated or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It can’t explain why the National Security Agency collects data about the privacy of Americans and why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are being punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential election.
It doesn’t justify the results of a report that says the White House’s efforts to silence the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood by the age of 18 that government work could contradict its previous political campaigns.
Obviously, the office of MP is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shape the public discussion.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unexplored alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope that we had heard about for so long.
But with Obama’s approval ratings dropping to less than 45% this week, the book’s return to 2008 has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have been dissolved in air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to make a heavy loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania by-elections.
In a meeting with the electoral assistants after the decision, he told his employees that they would have to get back on track and follow the purpose of their case.
“I want us to find our magic,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree more.
