On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical care to remote villages in Cameroon
Wave and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients.
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for every 5,000 people.
Tune in here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as the "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the resources to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation developed that spread to his brain and there caused a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle’s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is 413 for a doctor.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer left in Bwelle the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
In addition, he founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and ride on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help with the laced medical equipment.
Everything doesn't always go smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and the wave – with its wide smile and its boundless energy – is happy to be part of the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team begins investigating hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per trip,” says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and this on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply can’t afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall, or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is supplied by the generator of the group and thus Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early morning hours on Sunday.
It’s an exhausting thought, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then returns to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries in the past year and knows that its work makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a broken bar that he had received now allows him to work again.
“That changes the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, says Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for her second year and is a volunteer with Bwelle’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O’Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Wave, this is a chance to gain practical experiences they would never get at home.
“We can be in surgery, where we can help bleed or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” explains O’Malley.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
Once in Yaoundé, however, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He’s definitely a hero,” says O’Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For the wave, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father, brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
