At a length of about 120 metres, a Roman-era sewer is preserved below Cologne.
Anyone who visits Cologne does not pass by the cathedral.
Around 157 meters, the two towers rise into the sky and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who admire the two filigree church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the dome.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne’s underworld.
The meeting point for his tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourism directly at the Cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground garage," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore only what was not too big remained of the remnants of the old city wall.
Therefore, most users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and leave only their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal lattice bars in the Parkdeck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins made of hand-plate-sized stones.
"These are the remains of the Roman city wall, which was built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze says.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper parking level take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old dome, which unfortunately is also hardly perceived.
The next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend into the depths again.
Here we experience the office of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "city of Roman law and city of the Agrippinians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the exhibition hall, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at a length of about 120 meters.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze said.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After getting the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep, walkable shaft.
“We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath,” he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the ground water, which was essential for the ritual washings.
To this day, at the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins go back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by varying levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is expected to begin soon.
However, a few more years will pass until completion.
